explanation:
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro controls early return/abort behavior when task_id is NULL. Its expansion determines control flow and whether the subsequent operations are ever executed; removing the macro invocation or changing it could change program behaviour.
- OS_TaskValidateSystemData_Impl: The function's return value and side-effects decide whether the later object-search/assignment code runs. If this impl always fails/succeeds or has side-effects, it affects whether the later code is alive or removable.
- OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch: Central call that performs the search and returns OS_SUCCESS when the token is populated. Its contract (side-effects, when it may return OS_SUCCESS, and any external state changes) is needed to judge whether the call or its results are necessary.
- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: Converts the token to an osal_id_t. Must know whether it copies state (no side-effects) or modifies token/global state; this affects whether the assignment to *task_id is required for correct behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases/cleans up the token. Whether this has important side-effects (resource release, transactions finishing) determines if the call is removable (i.e., dead) without changing behavior.
- OS_object_token_t (type/definition): Structure/representation of the token is needed to understand whether FromToken/Release share/modify internal state (aliasing, ownership), which affects whether either operation is required.
- osal_id_t (type/definition): Type/semantics of the returned id (and whether copying it is meaningful) are necessary to decide if the assignment is a consequential operation.
- OS_SUCCESS (macro/constant): The success return value used in control flow; knowing its value and semantics is required to determine which branches are executed and if they can be removed.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL (macro/constant) and LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE (macro/constant): These parameters to OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch can affect the behavior/side-effects of the search (scope, locking, object set). Their semantics are relevant to decide whether the call is required for program behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish (impl called by OS_ObjectIdRelease): Because OS_ObjectIdRelease delegates to lower-level transaction/cleanup functions, the actual effects (commit/cleanup) performed there determine if omitting the Release call would change behaviour.

These symbols are the minimal set required to determine whether the operations performed in OS_TaskFindIdBySystemData (the validation call, the search, the id extraction, and the token release) have observable side-effects such that removing any of them would alter program behaviour (i.e., to decide if they are dead code under MISRA's definition).
